    <!-- SCIENCE SECTION -->
    <h2 id="science">The Science Behind Glutathione: What Clinical Research Shows</h2>

    <p>Glutathione is one of the most extensively studied antioxidant molecules in human biology, with over 160,000 published studies indexed in PubMed. The clinical evidence for oral glutathione supplementation has grown substantially in the past decade, with randomized controlled trials demonstrating benefits for skin health, immune function, and oxidative stress biomarkers. Understanding this evidence helps consumers evaluate which benefits are well-supported versus preliminary.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Skin brightening: strong evidence</strong>
        <p>A 2017 RCT found 250mg oral glutathione daily for 12 weeks significantly reduced melanin index and improved skin brightness. A 2020 study confirmed reduced and oxidized forms both produce skin lightening effects through tyrosinase inhibition.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Antioxidant capacity: strong evidence</strong>
        <p>A 2015 clinical trial demonstrated that 500mg Setria glutathione daily for 6 months significantly increased blood glutathione stores and natural killer cell activity, confirming that oral supplementation effectively raises systemic glutathione levels.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Liver detoxification: moderate evidence</strong>
        <p>Glutathione is the primary substrate for Phase II liver detoxification. Clinical data shows supplementation improves markers of liver function in individuals with non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) at doses of 300mg or more daily.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Anti-aging and longevity: emerging evidence</strong>
        <p>Glutathione levels decline approximately 10% per decade after age 20. Observational studies associate higher glutathione levels with reduced age-related disease markers, though interventional longevity trials are still ongoing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Important bioavailability context:</strong> Oral glutathione absorption has historically been debated in the scientific community. Earlier studies questioned whether glutathione survives digestion intact. However, more recent research using improved assay methods — including the 2015 Setria clinical trial — has confirmed that oral glutathione supplementation does increase circulating glutathione levels, particularly in reduced (active) form. Liposomal delivery further addresses bioavailability concerns by protecting the molecule from digestive degradation.</p>
    </div>

